title: For Sale:  Webley Large Wedge Frame 44 Cal Revolver
postcontent: This gun features a "Kerr" style percussion ball tamper bar and a 2 piece construction of the barrel unit and frame unit which are held together by a "wedge" or key, like a Colt revolver/ This design is much cheaper to produce as it eliminates the machining including boring and rifling with limited access. It also causes the cylinder pin access through the under barrel lug to become redundant as the cylinder is easily removed after separating the two major units. Very similar to a percussion Colt but the British design adds a top-strap for much more rigidity. Relatively few wedge frame guns were made however, due to the transition to cartridge revolvers and screw into frame barrels. This example wedge frame is of the earliest designs evident by deep 3 groove rifling. It has fine floral and single line engraving including large numbers on the cylinder, for reference during heat of battle. Finish is blue turning splotchy brown, and patina on "in the white" rammer, trigger and hammer. It is in Fine condition, all original parts, smoothest double action and light trigger for single action. Grips very nice, undamaged, just a few bumps on one side and tiny fill at top on one side. No pitting inside or out (including bore). The original nipples look unfired. Lock-up tight, correct functioning of action perfect.

title: For Sale:  .30 Caliber Browning ANM2 aircraft machine gun, fixed - Fully Functioning 30-06 Springfield
postcontent: .30 Caliber Browning ANM2 Aircraft Machine Gun - Fully Functioning 30-06 SpringfieldThe Browning .30 caliber is a work of art. It weighs nearly 1/3 less than it's ground cousin weighs. Virtually every part has been machined to reduce its weight. With a 300 mile per hour slip stream to cool it, the barrel can be thin and light. The military version is the Browning ANM2, the Colt commercial version is the MG40. It was used in both single and twin mounts, and as a fixed wing gun up until WW2 when it was realized that the .30 caliber round was simply too light to take out modern fighter aircraft. It was replaced but the .50 caliber M2. John Browning worked with the Belgian military and developed the FN series of guns, the FN30 ground gun and the FN38 & 39 aircraft guns. During WW2 the .30 caliber Browning was primarily used in training. This specific machine gun was purchased and repaired by our gunsmith's over the course of a year. This machine gun accepts 30-06 Springfield round, but if you remove a tiny plate it will accept the native round. Tested five days ago on the range, fully functioning. If you have any questions or would like more pictures feel free to contact me!

title: For Sale:  STEYR ARMS SCOUT 308WIN 19" GREY
postcontent:
The Steyr Scout provides the ideal solution for versatility, durability, accuracy and reliability in a compact and lightweight bolt-action rifle platform. Developed in a nearly decade-long collaboration with legendary Marine Corps Lt.Col. Jeff Cooper, the Scout boasts an extensive list of innovative features.
The lightweight bolt-action, all-purpose Steyr Scout rifle was designed to accept a low-powered, forward-mounted scope for accurate fire and both-eyes-open operation to detect flanking dangers. Backup “ghost-ring” iron sights integrated to the top rail can be deployed within seconds should the optics fail. The rifle can also be fitted with a standard scope, should the need arise.
In keeping with Cooper’s requirement for a magazine cutoff, Steyr incorporated a two-position magazine system that allowed the rifle to be fed individually with the five-round magazine in a lowered position. The magazine could be seated one step further with minimal pressure, allowing the bolt to feed cartridges directly from the magazine. A second five-round backup magazine is contained in the buttstock in case of an urgent need to reload.
With a fluted, cold-hammer-forged barrel measuring 19 inches, an overall length of 38.6 inches and an out-of-the-box weight of just 6.6 pounds, the Scout is a breeze to pack out on long adventures, patrolling the farm or taking a quick trip to the range. The compact design of the stock features an innovative integrated bipod that is hardly noticeable until it is folded out from the stock. Between the bipod legs is a UIT rail for attachments, and the stock is outfitted with five press-and-twist sling-swivel attachment points that allow the addition of Cooper’s favored Ching Sling on either side of the rifle.
The Steyr Scout is built on the Safe Bolt System (SBS) action with a unique 2+1 safety function that offers three settings operated by a wheel switch on the tang of the stock. The FIRE mode (safety off) is indicated by a red dot, and the first level of SAFE mode disables the firing mechanism while allowing the bolt to be cycled. The second SAFE position locks the bolt, at which point the bolt can be pushed down against the stock, locking the firing pin and firing mechanism out of firing position, allowing safe transportation with a round in the chamber. Simply pressing the safety’s release tab and rolling it forward returns the bolt to either the SAFE or the FIRE position.
The unique features make the Scout a self-contained platform that can easily be carried in a rifle scabbard without any need for attaching/detaching a bipod or finding extra pockets for a spare magazine, perfect for use on horseback, ATV or on a vehicle rifle rack.

title: For Trade:  Fabrique Nationale Pre-War Browning Auto 5 Shotgun
postcontent: This is an early example of an A5 likely made sometime between 1903-1939. It was made in Belgium by Fabrique Nationale (FN Herstal) for Browning Arms. It is one of roughly 10,000 made in that era and likely one of the few left surviving. I'd put it being made sometime in the 1920s. All my research into it states that it is an "unmarked" 16. Usually the 16 gauges were marked as "sweet 16s", but only from around 1949 on. This is a decently rare example as it pre-dates those, and still has the enhancements and engravings. For it's age, it is in great shape and hasn't been shot much over its life. Conservatively, I'd say that the overall finish is about 80%, if not more. Wood is in great shape as well. Factory Engraving is also easily visible. It is all original and a great addition to any collection.

postcontent: Most of these were used up by market hunters. Production ceased abruptly when 8 gauges were outlawed for hunting. This one has been shot very little and retains over 90% of the original case coloring. It locks up tight and the breech faces show very little firing wear. 31" fancy damascus barrels that retain over 90% of the original damascus pattern. Excellent bores with no dents or pitting. Wood is also excellent with no cracks or repairs. Wood has the expected handling marks for a 130 year old gun. LOP is 14 3/8" and drop is 1 3/4" and 3". Hard rubber buttplate has warped a little. Barrels have probably been shortened from 34" to 31". Gun comes in a Browning leather case with 12 empty Remington 8 gauge cases. A rare find. Johnstone emigrated from England to Pittsburgh and imported English guns in the white and finished them under his name. I have had other Westley Richards and Scott patent guns finished and retailed by him and all have been high quality as this one is. Gun has English proofs,
